The paper deals with the problem of computing stable matchings in large markets, which is a classic topic in algorithmic game theory (cs.GT). The use of differential privacy is a key component of the proposed mechanism, which suggests that the paper could also be relevant to the subfield of cryptography (cs.CR). The algorithmic techniques used in the paper involve data structures and algorithms for computing matchings, which could fall under the category of data structures (cs.DS). The use of machine learning techniques for differential privacy could also make the paper relevant to the subfield of machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper proposes a mechanism for computing school optimal matchings that is truthful for students, which could be relevant to the subfield of artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
